{{Infobox museum | name =San Diego Hall of Champions | native_name = | native_name_lang = | logo = | logo_upright = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = | image = San Diego Hall of Champions.jpg | image_upright = | alt = | caption = San Diego Hall of Champions | map_type = United States San Diego#California#USA | map_relief = | map_size = | map_caption = | coordinates ={{Coord|32|43|38.39|N|117|09|08.29|W|display=title, inline}} | former_name = | established = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | dissolved = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | location = [[San Diego]], [[California]], [[US]] | type = | accreditation = | key_holdings = | collections = | collection_size = | visitors = | founder = | director = | president = | ceo = | chairperson = | curator = | architect = | historian = | owner = | publictransit = | car_park = | parking = | network = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | embedded = }}
The '''San Diego Hall of Champions''' was an American multi-sport museum in [[San Diego]], [[California]]. It was recognized as the largest multi-sport museum in the United States until its closure in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiego.com/attractions/san-diego-hall-champions-sports-museum|title=San Diego Hall of Champions Sports Museum|website=www.sandiego.com}}</ref> Located in the Federal Building in [[Balboa Park, San Diego, California|Balboa Park]] until 2017, the {{convert|70000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} facility recognized outstanding athletic accomplishments and traditions involving more than forty-two sports until June 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fox5sandiego.com/2017/06/15/hall-of-champions-closes-its-doors-in-balboa-park/|title=Hall of Champions closes its doors in Balboa Park|date=15 June 2017|website=fox5sandiego.com}}</ref>. The Hall of Champions was founded in 1959 and includes the Breitbard Hall of Fame which is being relocated to be displayed at Petco Park.
==Breitbard Hall of Fame== [[File:Breitbard Hall of Fame.jpg|thumb|right|The Breitbard Hall of Fame]] The Breitbard [[Hall of Fame]] was established in 1953 by Robert Breitbard.<ref name=BreitbardHOF>[http://www.sdhoc.com/hall-of-fame Breitbard Hall of Fame] webpage. San Diego Hall of Champions website. Retrieved 2011-03-19.</ref> It honors athletes who either (1) have excelled in sports in San Diego or (2) are native San Diegans who have excelled in sports elsewhere.<ref name=BreitbardHOF/> As of 2008, 117 athletes have been inducted, representing 20 sports: archery; badminton and tennis; baseball; basketball; bowling; boxing; diving and swimming; football; figure skating; golf; hockey; horse racing; marksmanship; motor sports; pole vaulting; sailing; skateboarding; soccer; track and field; triathlon; and wrestling.<ref name=BreitbardHOF/> New members are inducted in February at the Salute to the Champions dinner.<ref name=BreitbardHOF/>
===Eligibility=== To be eligible for enshrinement, the candidate must meet these criteria:<ref>[http://www.sdhoc.com/hof-nomination-form Breitbard Hall of Fame Nomination Form] webpage. San Diego Hall of Champions website. Retrieved 2011-03-19.</ref> *An athlete, coach or special contributor native to San Diego county or who represented a San Diego high school, university, sports organization or professional team *Professional athletes not native to San Diego county must have spent at least 4 years of their career in San Diego *Athletes must be retired for at least 2 years or be at least 50 years old *Coaches and contributors do not need to be retired, but must have spent at least 7 years working in their field
